      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute brisk walk to ease into movement. Focus on relaxed breathing and upright posture.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace — you should be able to speak in full sentences. If you feel breathless, slow down or walk briefly. This is aerobic base building, not a test.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a walk for the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate come down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute brisk walk. Add 4–6 dynamic movements: leg swings, hip circles, and ankle rolls. No static stretching before running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes, then hold 3–4 gentle static stretches — calves, hip flexors, and quads — for 20–30 seconds each.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. At your current fitness level, building aerobic base is the single most important thing you can do. Running at a truly easy pace (7:00–8:00 /km) trains your cardiovascular system, strengthens connective tissue, and builds the aerobic engine that will power your 5K. The goal here is consistency and comfort — not speed. If 30 minutes feels like a lot, it is absolutely fine to walk-run your way through it. Every minute on your feet counts.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Run-Walk Intervals — Building Stamina\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":420,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute brisk walk to warm up. Focus on tall posture and relaxed shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":435,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"Run for 4 minutes at a comfortably brisk pace (around 7:00–7:30 /km), then walk for 1 minute. Repeat 4 times. The walk breaks are intentional — use them to recover and maintain quality on the running portions.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes. Shake out your legs and breathe deeply.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5-minute brisk walk followed by leg swings and hip circles. Take your time — a good warmup sets the tone for the whole session.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes, then stretch calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors. Hold each stretch for 20–30 seconds without bouncing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This mid-week session introduces a gentle structure to your running. The 4-minute run / 1-minute walk format lets you accumulate more quality running time than a continuous run might allow at this stage, while keeping fatigue manageable. Over the coming weeks, you will gradually extend the running intervals and shorten the walks. Think of this as a staircase — each week you climb one step. The pace on the running portions should feel brisk but controlled, not a sprint. If 4 minutes feels too long, 3 minutes is a perfectly valid starting point.\",\"perceived_effort\":5},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run — Easy and Steady\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":480,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":480,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":510,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute walk. This is your longest session of the week — start conservatively and let your body settle in.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easiest comfortable pace — 7:30–8:00 /km or slower if needed. Walk breaks are completely fine whenever you need them. The goal is time on feet, not pace. Stay relaxed, breathe comfortably, and enjoy the process.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":510,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes to bring your heart rate down. You have earned this.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute walk. On long run days, your warmup IS the first 10 minutes of easy running — let your body ease into the effort gradually rather than rushing to pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 5 minutes after finishing. Spend 5–8 minutes on full-body stretching — calves, quads, hip flexors, glutes, and lower back. Hydrate well and consider a light snack within 30–45 minutes if you feel hungry.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday's long run is the cornerstone of your 5K preparation. Even though 5K feels like a short race, the long run builds the aerobic foundation, strengthens your musculoskeletal system, and develops the mental resilience that race day demands. At 6 km this week — just slightly beyond your current 5 km long run — the progression is intentional and conservative. Your body adapts between sessions, not during them, so the easy pace here is non-negotiable. Going slower than feels necessary is almost always the right call on long run day. Walk breaks are a tool, not a sign of weakness — use them freely.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
